      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "gist:Component",
      "@type": "owl:Class",
      "owl:disjointWith": {
        "@id": "gist:PhysicalSubstance"
      },
      "rdfs:comment": [
        "DEFINITION: Something that, while having an independent existence, is inherently part of or designed to be part of a larger entity, such as a system or network.",
        "NOTE: This class is not disjoint with gist:Composite, because a component may itself break down into smaller components.",
        "NOTE: Physical substances, such as ingredients in a cake batter, do not meet the independent existence criterion, so are not components.",
        "NOTE: Many things are in a trivial sense a part of a larger thing, but are not considered components because they are not inherently part of that larger thing. For example, while a book may be part of a library (a collection of books), it is not inherently so, and thus is not a component. A playing card, on the other hand, could be considered a component in (member of) a deck of cards. This may be use case-dependent; e.g., car parts might be modeled as components in an automobile manufacturing context but not in a retail auto parts store.",
        "NOTE: A component may be designed or intended as part of a whole without actually being so; e.g., a car steering wheel that is not installed in any car.",
        "NOTE: This is an abstract class that is not directly instantiated. Users will define subclasses that are meaningful to their domain of interest."
      ],
      "rdfs:isDefinedBy": {
        "@id": "https://w3id.org/semanticarts/ontology/gistCore14.1.0"
      },
      "rdfs:label": "Component",
      "skos:definition": "Something that, while having an independent existence, is inherently part of or designed to be part of a larger entity, such as a system or network.",
      "skos:prefLabel": "Component",
      "skos:scopeNote": [
        "Physical substances, such as ingredients in a cake batter, do not meet the independent existence criterion, so are not components.",
        "This is an abstract class that is not directly instantiated. Users will define subclasses that are meaningful to their domain of interest.",
        "This class is not disjoint with gist:Composite, because a component may itself break down into smaller components.",
        "Many things are in a trivial sense a part of a larger thing, but are not considered components because they are not inherently part of that larger thing. For example, while a book may be part of a library (a collection of books), it is not inherently so, and thus is not a component. A playing card, on the other hand, could be considered a component in (member of) a deck of cards. This may be use case-dependent; e.g., car parts might be modeled as components in an automobile manufacturing context but not in a retail auto parts store.",
        "A component may be designed or intended as part of a whole without actually being so; e.g., a car steering wheel that is not installed in any car."
      ]
    },
